{"title_page": "2016 Cebu City local elections", "text_new": "{{short description|Election in Cebu City, Philippines on 2016}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2016 Cebu City mayoral election\n| flag_image = \n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2013 Cebu City local elections\n| previous_year = 2013\n| next_election = 2019 Cebu City local elections\n| next_year = 2019\n| election_date = May 9, 2016\n| image1 = [[File:Tommy Osme\u00f1a 2017 (cropped).jpg|140x150px]]\n| nominee1 = '''[[Tomas Osme\u00f1a]]'''\n| party1 = Liberal Party (Philippines)\n| running_mate1 = Nestor Archival\n| popular_vote1 = '''266,819'''\n| percentage1 = '''53.40'''\n| image2 = [[File:Michael Lopez Rama.jpg|140x150px]]\n| nominee2 = [[Mike Rama|Michael Rama]]\n| party2 = United Nationalist Alliance\n| running_mate2 =  '''[[Edgardo Labella]]'''\n| popular_vote2 = 232,925\n| percentage2 = 46.60\n| title = [[Mayor of Cebu City|Mayor]]\n| before_election = [[Mike Rama|Michael Rama]]\n| after_election = [[Tommy Osme\u00f1a]]\n| before_party = [[United Nationalist Alliance]]\n| after_party = Liberal Party (Philippines)\n}}\n'''Local elections''' were held in '''[[Cebu City]]''' on May 9, 2016 within the [[2016 Philippine general election|Philippine general election]]. Registered voters of the city elected candidates for the following elective local posts: mayor, vice mayor, district representative, and eight councilors [[at-large]] for each district. There are two legislative districts in the city.\n\n[[Tomas Osme\u00f1a]], who previously served as [[Mayor of Cebu City]], defeated incumbent [[Mike Rama|Michael Rama]] who was seeking for his third and last term by a margin of 33,894 votes.<ref name=\"CC1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2016/132519-tommy-osmena-cebu-city-mayor|title=Osme\u00f1a is Cebu City's mayor-elect {{!}} Rappler|website=rappler.com|access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref>\n\n==Mayoralty and vice mayoralty elections==\n\n===Mayor===\n[[Mike Rama|Michael Rama]] ran for his third and last term as the [[Mayor of Cebu City]] but was defeated by former Mayor [[Tomas Osme\u00f1a]], who ran against Rama for the second time since losing to him in the [[2013 Cebu City local elections|2013 elections]].<ref name=\"CC2\">{{Cite web|url=http://2016halalanresults.abs-cbn.com/local/9/26/470/cebu-city.html|title=Halalan 2016 Results: Cebu City {{!}} ABS-CBN Halalan 2016|website=2016halalanresults.abs-cbn.com|access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref>\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Cebu City mayoral election}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party = Liberal Party (Philippines)\n  |candidate = [[Tomas Osme\u00f1a]]\n  |votes = 266,819\n  |percentage = 53.40\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party = United Nationalist Alliance\n  |candidate = [[Mike Rama|Michael Rama]] ([[incumbent]])\n  |votes = 232,925\n  |percentage = 46.60\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n  |votes = 499744\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box margin of victory no change|\n  |votes      = 33,894\n  |percentage = 6.80\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link without swing\n    |winner = Liberal Party (Philippines)\n    |loser  = United Nationalist Alliance\n    |swing  =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Vice Mayor===\n[[Edgardo Labella]] ran for his second term as the [[Mayor of Cebu City#Vice Mayor of Cebu City|Vice Mayor of Cebu City]] and defeated incumbent Cebu City Councilor for the North District Nestor Archival.<ref name=\"CC2\"/>\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Cebu City Vice mayoral election}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party = United Nationalist Alliance\n  |candidate = [[Edgardo Labella]] ([[incumbent]])\n  |votes = 252,201\t\n  |percentage = 53.15\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party = Liberal Party (Philippines)\n  |candidate = Nestor Archival\n  |votes = 222,337\n  |percentage = 46.85\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n  |votes = 474538\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box margin of victory no change|\n  |votes      = 29,864\n  |percentage = 6.30\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no swing\n    |winner = United Nationalist Alliance\n    |loser  = \n    |swing  =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District representatives==\n\n===1st District===\n[[Raul del Mar]] ran for his second term, and won.\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title=2016 Philippine House of Representatives election in the [[Legislative districts of Cebu City|1st District of Cebu City]]\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n   |party      = Liberal Party (Philippines)\n   |candidate  = [[Raul del Mar]] ([[incumbent]])\n   |votes      = 134,940\n   |percentage = 66.26\n}}\n {{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n   |party      = United Nationalist Alliance\n   |candidate  = Alvin Garcia\n   |votes      = 64,348\n   |percentage = 31.60\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n   |party      = Independent (politician)\n   |candidate  = Ricardo Adlawan\n   |votes      = 2,400\n   |percentage = 1.18\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n   |party      = Independent (politician)\n   |candidate  = Juan Arenasa\n   |votes      = 1,952\n   |percentage = 0.96\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n   |votes      = 203640\n   |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box margin of victory no change|\n  |votes      = 70,592\n  |percentage = 34.66\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing\n   |winner     = Liberal Party (Philippines)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2nd District===\n[[Rodrigo Abellanosa]] ran for his second term, and won.\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title=2016 Philippine House of Representatives election in the [[Legislative districts of Cebu City|2nd District of Cebu City]]\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n   |party      = Liberal Party (